Here's a complete health-check runbook for the two-node external Loki cluster. Run these from the Loki hosts (they have `docker` and `curl`). I've grouped them so you can work top-down: containers → ring → memberlist → storage → limits → end-to-end → the OpenShift collector side.

## 1. Container status (both nodes)

```bash
# On loki1
docker ps --format "table {{.Names}}\t{{.Status}}\t{{.Ports}}" | grep -E "loki|redis|prometheus"
# On loki2 (same command)

# Anything restarting/unhealthy? — should return nothing
docker ps --filter "health=unhealthy" --format "{{.Names}}"
docker ps -a --filter "status=restarting" --format "{{.Names}}"

# Restart counts — all should be low/stable, not climbing
docker ps -a --format "{{.Names}}" | grep loki | while read c; do
  echo "$c restarts=$(docker inspect -f '{{.RestartCount}}' $c)"
done
```

## 2. Per-component readiness (both nodes)

Each Loki target exposes `/ready`. Node1 ports 3100–3107, Node2 same HTTP ports.

```bash
# Node1 (10.189.35.10)
for p in 3100 3101 3102 3103 3104 3105 3106 3107; do
  echo -n "node1:$p /ready -> "; curl -s -o /dev/null -w "%{http_code}\n" http://10.189.35.10:$p/ready
done

# Node2 (10.189.35.11)
for p in 3100 3101 3102 3103 3104 3105 3106 3107; do
  echo -n "node2:$p /ready -> "; curl -s -o /dev/null -w "%{http_code}\n" http://10.189.35.11:$p/ready
done
```
All should return `200`. A `503` means that component is still joining or unhealthy.

## 3. Ring health — the most important check

```bash
# Ingester ring — expect 4 ACTIVE total (2 per node), no UNHEALTHY/LEAVING/PENDING
curl -s http://10.189.35.10:3100/ring | grep -Eo "ACTIVE|UNHEALTHY|LEAVING|PENDING|JOINING" | sort | uniq -c

# Cross-check from node2's view — must show the SAME 4 ACTIVE
curl -s http://10.189.35.11:3100/ring | grep -Eo "ACTIVE|UNHEALTHY|LEAVING|PENDING|JOINING" | sort | uniq -c

# Distributor ring
curl -s "http://10.189.35.10:3100/distributor/ring" | grep -Eo "ACTIVE|UNHEALTHY" | sort | uniq -c

# Compactor ring (1 compactor per node = 2)
curl -s "http://10.189.35.10:3107/compactor/ring" | grep -Eo "ACTIVE|UNHEALTHY" | sort | uniq -c
```
Both nodes must report the **same** ring membership. If node1 sees 4 ACTIVE but node2 sees 2, memberlist isn't converging (check section 4).

## 4. Memberlist / cluster gossip

```bash
# Total members in gossip — you have ~14 components across both nodes
curl -s http://10.189.35.10:3100/memberlist | grep -c "10.189.35"

# Same count from node2 — should match node1
curl -s http://10.189.35.11:3100/memberlist | grep -c "10.189.35"

# Look for gossip errors (EOF, connection refused, failed to connect)
docker logs loki-distributor-primary-1-node1   2>&1 | grep -i "memberlist" | grep -iE "err|fail|refused" | tail -10
docker logs loki-distributor-secondary-1-node2 2>&1 | grep -i "memberlist" | grep -iE "err|fail|refused" | tail -10
```
Both nodes should report the same member count. Occasional EOF on reconnect is normal; repeated "failed to connect" to a specific IP:port is not.

## 5. Object storage (S3) connectivity — only ingesters/compactor write

```bash
# Confirm ingesters are flushing chunks to S3 (no errors). Recent flushes = healthy.
docker logs --since 10m loki-ingester-primary-1-node1   2>&1 | grep -iE "flush|s3|error" | grep -iv "level=info.*flushing stream" | tail -15
docker logs --since 10m loki-ingester-secondary-1-node2 2>&1 | grep -iE "flush|s3|error" | grep -iv "level=info.*flushing stream" | tail -15

# Positive signal: you SHOULD see "flushing stream" info lines
docker logs --since 5m loki-ingester-primary-1-node1 2>&1 | grep -c "flushing stream"

# Compactor reaching S3 (no auth/endpoint errors)
docker logs --since 15m loki-compactor-node1 2>&1 | grep -iE "s3|error|compact" | tail -15

# Direct S3 reachability from the host (TLS + DNS to the NetApp endpoint)
curl -s -o /dev/null -w "S3 endpoint -> %{http_code}\n" https://s3store-A9cl2-pr.bank.sbi
```
The S3 endpoint returning `403`/`400` to a bare curl is fine (it means it's reachable but needs auth/signing) — what you don't want is a timeout or TLS error. The key positive signal is ingesters logging `flushing stream` with no S3 errors alongside.

## 6. Confirm the limit fixes actually took effect

This is the verification that your 429 fix is live:

```bash
# Dump the runtime config the distributor actually loaded and check the rate values
curl -s http://10.189.35.10:3100/config | grep -iE "ingestion_rate_mb|ingestion_burst_size_mb|ingestion_rate_strategy|max_line_size|reject_old_samples|per_stream_rate_limit"
curl -s http://10.189.35.11:3100/config | grep -iE "ingestion_rate_mb|ingestion_burst_size_mb|ingestion_rate_strategy|max_line_size|reject_old_samples|per_stream_rate_limit"
```
Expect to see `ingestion_rate_mb: 256`, `ingestion_burst_size_mb: 512`, `ingestion_rate_strategy: local`, `max_line_size: 4194304`, `reject_old_samples: false`. If `/config` shows the old values, the container wasn't recreated (you did `restart` instead of `down`/`up`).

```bash
# No NEW rate-limit rejections in the last few minutes on any distributor
for n in 10.189.35.10 10.189.35.11; do
  echo "== $n =="
done
docker logs --since 5m loki-distributor-primary-1-node1   2>&1 | grep -ic "rate limit exceeded"
docker logs --since 5m loki-distributor-primary-2-node1   2>&1 | grep -ic "rate limit exceeded"
docker logs --since 5m loki-distributor-secondary-1-node2 2>&1 | grep -ic "rate limit exceeded"
docker logs --since 5m loki-distributor-secondary-2-node2 2>&1 | grep -ic "rate limit exceeded"
```
All four counts should be `0` (or steeply dropping). Any non-zero and still-climbing count means a distributor is still on old config or volume genuinely exceeds 256 MB/s.

## 7. End-to-end write + read test

Prove the cluster actually accepts and returns data:

```bash
# Push a test log line (auth disabled, tenant "fake")
NOW=$(date +%s%N)
curl -s -o /dev/null -w "push -> %{http_code}\n" -X POST http://10.189.35.10:3100/loki/api/v1/push \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"streams":[{"stream":{"job":"healthcheck","node":"manual"},"values":[["'$NOW'","loki-cluster-healthcheck-test"]]}]}'
# Expect 204

# Read it back via the query-frontend (port 3104)
sleep 3
curl -s -G "http://10.189.35.10:3104/loki/api/v1/query_range" \
  --data-urlencode 'query={job="healthcheck"}' \
  --data-urlencode "start=$(date -d '5 min ago' +%s)000000000" \
  --data-urlencode "end=$(date +%s)000000000" | head -c 500; echo
```
A `204` on push and your test string appearing in the query result = the full write→ingest→query path works on the cluster.

## 8. Resource pressure (catches the slow-burn problems)

```bash
# CPU/mem per container — watch for ingesters pinned at memory limit
docker stats --no-stream --format "table {{.Name}}\t{{.CPUPerc}}\t{{.MemUsage}}\t{{.MemPerc}}" | grep -E "loki|redis"

# Disk on the WAL/data path — full disk = ingesters stop flushing
df -h /data/loki
```

## 9. The OpenShift collector side (does Grafana actually get logs now)

```bash
# 429/400 should be gone; 204s flowing. Sample a few grafana collectors:
for p in $(oc -n openshift-logging get po -o name | grep collector-grafana | head -5); do
  echo "== $p =="
  oc -n openshift-logging logs ${p#pod/} --since=5m | grep -Eic "429|too many"
done
